{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox writer | name = Anuradha Ramanan | image = Anuradha Ramanan.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{birth date|1947|06|29|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Thanjavur]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2010|5|16|1947|6|29|df=y}} | death_place = [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]], India | occupation = {{Flatlist| * Writer * novelist * artist * social activist }} | period = 1977—2010 | genre = | subject = | movement = | signature = | website = }}
'''Anuradha Ramanan''' (29 June 1947 – 16 May 2010)<ref>{{cite web|title=Noted writer Anuradha Ramanan passes away|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/tamil-nadu/noted-writer-anuradha-ramanan-passes-away_627217.html|publisher=[[Zee News]]|accessdate=17 August 2013|date=2010-05-16}}</ref> was a [[Tamil people|Tamil]] writer, artist and a social activist.
==Biography== Anuradha was born in 1947 in [[Thanjavur]], Tamil Nadu. Her grandfather [[R. Balasubramaniam]] was an actor who inspired Anuradha to become a writer.<ref name=Express>{{cite news|title=Popular Tamil writer Anuradha Ramanan dead|url=http://newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/article271406.ece?commentId=103962|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=17 May 2010}}</ref> Anuradha started her career as an artist before making several unsuccessful attempts to get a job with popular magazines.<ref name=Express /> This prompted her to join ''Mangai'', a Tamil magazine after the editor found her writings very interesting. Anuradha's literary career started in 1977 while working for the magazine.<ref name=Express />
Apart from her literary contributions, she was well known for her "anti-divorce counselling" work.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saadhanai Penn – Anuradha Ramanan|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2003/11/21/stories/2003112101060800.htm|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=21 November 2003}}</ref> In a career that spanned over 30 years, Anuradha wrote nearly 800 novels and 1,230 short stories.<ref name=Express /> Her works were mainly centered on family and everyday happenings. One of her early works ''Sirai'', won a gold medal for the best short story from ''[[Ananda Vikatan]]''.<ref name=hindu1>{{cite news|title=Anuradha Ramanan dead|url=http://www.hindu.com/2010/05/17/stories/2010051756100500.htm|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=17 May 2010}}</ref> It was adapted into a film of the same name.<ref name=hindu1 /> Following this, her other novels ''[[Kootu Puzhukkal]]'', ''[[Oru Malarin Payanam]]'' and ''Oru Veedu Iruvasal'' were adapted into films in various languages such as Tamil, Telugu and Kannada.<ref name=Express /> ''[[Oru Veedu Iru Vasal]]'', directed by Balachander won the [[National Film Award for Best Film on Other Social Issues]] in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/38th_nff_1991.pdf|title=38th National Film Awards|format=PDF|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref> The 1988 Telugu film ''[[Oka Baarya Katha]]'' based on her work won five [[Nandi Awards]].<ref name=HT>{{cite news|title=Noted writer dead|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/Chennai/Noted-writer-dead/Article1-544558.aspx|accessdate=17 August 2013|newspaper=[[The Hindustan Times]]|date=16 May 2010}}</ref> In addition to films, many of her stories such as ''Archanai Pookal'', ''Paasam'' and ''Kanakanden Thozhi'' have been adapted into [[Soap opera|television serials]].<ref name=hindu1 /> She was awarded a gold medal by [[M. G. Ramachandran]], the then [[Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu]].<ref name=hindu1 />
===Death=== Anuradha died of cardiac arrest on 16 May 2010 at the age of 62 in [[Chennai]].<ref name=hindu1 /> She was married to Ramanan and has two daughters.<ref name=hindu1 />
