'''Cypriot Turkish''' ({{lang-tr|Kıbrıs Türkçesi}}) is a dialect of the [[Turkish language]] spoken by [[Turkish Cypriots]] both in [[Cyprus]] and among [[Turkish Cypriot diaspora|its diaspora]].

==History==
Emanating from [[Anatolia]] and evolved for four centuries, Cypriot Turkish is the [[vernacular]] spoken by Cypriots with [[Ottoman Turks|Ottoman]] ancestry, as well as by Cypriots who converted to [[Islam]] during Ottoman rule.<ref> Jennings, Ronald (1993), Christians and Muslims in Ottoman Cyprus and the Mediterranean World, 1571-1640, New York University Press {{ISBN|0-814-74181-9}}.</ref> It is understood by expatriate Cypriots living in the UK, United States, Australia and other parts of the world.

Cypriot Turkish consists of a blend of [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] and the [[Yörük]] dialect that is spoken in the [[Taurus Mountains]] of southern [[Turkey]]. In addition, it has absorbed influences from [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[English language|English]].

Cypriot Turkish is mutually intelligible with [[Turkish language|Standard Turkish]].

==Sounds==

===Differences between standard Turkish and Cypriot Turkish===
Cypriot Turkish is distinguished by a number of sound alternations not found in standard Turkish, but some of which are also quite common in other Turkish vernaculars:
* Voicing of some unvoiced [[stop consonant|stops]]
** t↔d, k↔g
::Standard Turkish {{lang|tr|taş}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish {{lang|tr-CY|daş}} "stone"
::Standard Turkish {{lang|tr|kurt}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish {{lang|tr-CY|gurt}} "wolf"
::Standard Turkish {{lang|tr|Kıbrıs}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish {{lang|tr-CY|Gıprıs}} "[[Cyprus]]"
* Preservation of earlier [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] {{lang|trk|*ŋ}}
::Standard Turkish {{lang|tr|son}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish {{lang|tr-CY|soŋ}} "end, last"
::Standard Turkish {{lang|tr|bin}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish {{lang|tr-CY|biŋ}} "thousand"
* Changing 1st person plural suffix
** z↔k
::Standard Turkish {{lang|tr|isteriz}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish {{lang|tr-CY|isterik}} "we want"
* Unvoicing of some voiced stops
** b↔p
::Standard Turkish: {{lang|tr|Arabaya binmek}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish: {{lang|tr-CY|Arabaya pinmek}} "Get in the car"{{cn |date=April 2018}}
* [[Lenition]] of final [[affricate]]s
** ç ({{IPA|[tʃ]}}) ↔ ş ({{IPA|[ʃ]}})
::Standard Turkish {{lang|tr|hiç}} ↔ Cypriot Turkish {{lang|tr-CY|hiş}} "no, none"

The last two alternations are more specific to Cypriot Turkish and are seen less often in other Turkish vernaculars.

