[[mk:Кипарски Турци]]

'''Enterprise journalism''' is [[Journalism|reporting]] that is not generated by [[news]] or a [[press release]], but rather generated by a [[reporter]] or [[news organization]] based on developed [[Journalism sourcing|sources]].<ref>{{ cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2193558/sidebar/2193648/|title=What is "enterprise journalism"|author=slate}}</ref> Tied to "[[Shoe-leather reporting|shoe-leather]]" reporting and "[[beat reporting]]," enterprise journalism gets the journalist out of the office and away from the traditional news makers. It also enlists some of the traditional traits of good investigative reporting, such as reading documents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjr.org/politics/enterprise_going_the_extra_mil.php|title=Enterprise: Going the Extra Mile|author=Columbia Journalism Review}}</ref>
Enterprise journalism does not involve reporting which is based purely on press releases or news conferences. On the other hand, this kind of reporting involves stories where a reporter unearths a story on his/her own; a lot of people refer to these as ‘scoops.' The enterprise reporting goes ahead of just reporting events; it discovers the forces that shape such events.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://journalism.about.com/od/reporting/a/enterprise.htm|title= Developing Stories That Go Beyond Press Releases|author=about.com}}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}
==External links== * [http://www.lostremote.com/2008/03/13/enterprise-journalism-is-not-a-commodity/ Enterprise journalism is not a commodity] * [http://zombiejournalism.com/2009/11/making-enterprise-journalism-web-reader-friendly/ Making enterprise journalism “web reader” friendly] * [http://www.facebook.com/pages/Enterprise-journalism/120257754687644 Enterprise Journalism on Facebook]
