{{Infobox language family |name=Maxakalían |region=[[Brazil]] |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Macro-Gê languages|Macro-Gê]] |glotto=maxa1246 |glottorefname=Maxakali |map=Maxkali languages.png |mapcaption= }}
The '''Maxakalían''' languages (also '''Mashakalían''') were first classified into the [[Gê languages]]. It was only in 1931 that Loukotka separated them from the Gê family. Alfred Métraux and Curt Nimuendaju Unkel considered the Maxakalían family isolated from others. [[John Alden Mason]] suggests a connection with the [[Macro-Gê]] stock, confirmed by Aryon Dall’Igna Rodrigues.
==Languages== Apart from extinct varieties generally seen as dialects of Maxakalí,<ref>Some listed as alternative names in {{ethnolink|mbl|Maxakali language}}</ref> Mason noted resemblances with a few other extinct languages of the area: [[Pataxó language|Pataxó]], [[Malalí language|Malalí]] and [[Coropó language|Coropó]]. However, Coropó is now thought to be a [[Purian languages|Purian]] language. Campbell (1997) therefore lists the Maxakalian languages as:
# '''[[Malalí language|Malalí]]''' ''(†)'' # '''[[Pataxó language|Pataxó]]''' (Patashó) ''(†)'' (retain some words) # '''[[Maxakalí language|Maxakalí]]''' (Mashacalí)
''Glottolog'' (2016) restores [[Coropó language|Coropó]] (Koropó) as a Maxakalían language.
