The alveolar nasal {{IPA|/n/}} is [[Homorganic consonants|assimilated]] to following [[obstruent]]s; it can be labiodental (e.g. {{lang|el|αμφιβολία}} {{IPA|[aɱfivoˈlia]}} 'doubt'), dental (e.g. {{lang|el|άνθος}} {{IPA|[ˈan̪θos]}} 'flower'), [[Relative articulation#Advanced and retracted|retracted]] alveolar (e.g. {{lang|el|πένσα}} {{IPA|[ˈpen̠sa]}} "pliers"), [[alveolo-palatal]] (e.g. {{lang|el|συγχύζω}} {{IPA|[siɲˈçizo]}} 'to annoy'), or velar (e.g. {{lang|el|άγχος}} {{IPA|[ˈaŋхos]}} 'stress').{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|pp=14–15}}

Voiceless stops are [[aspirated consonant|unaspirated]] and with a very short [[voice onset time]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=2}} They may be lightly voiced in rapid speech, especially when [[intervocalic consonant|intervocalic]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=7}} {{IPA|/t/}}'s exact [[place of articulation]] ranges from [[alveolar]] to [[denti-alveolar]], to [[dental consonant|dental]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=10}} It may be fricated {{IPA|[{{IPA link|θ̠}} ~ {{IPA link|θ}}]}} in rapid speech, and very rarely, in [[function word]]s, it is deleted.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=11}} {{IPA|/p/}} and {{IPA|/k/}} are reduced to lesser degrees in rapid speech.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=11}}

Voiced stops are [[prenasalised]] as reflected in the orthography to varying extents, or not at all.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=9}} The nasal component—when present—does not increase the duration of the stop's closure; as such, prenasalised voiced stops would be most accurately transcribed {{IPA|[ᵐb ⁿd ᵑɡ]}} or {{IPA|[m͡b, n͡d, ŋ͡ɡ]}}, depending on the length of the nasal component.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=9}} Word-initially and after {{IPA|/r/}} or {{IPA|/l/}}, they are very rarely, if ever, prenasalised.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|p=2}}{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=10}} In rapid and casual speech, prenasalisation is generally rarer, and voiced stops may be lenited to fricatives.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=10}} This also accounts for Greeks having trouble disambiguating voiced stops, nasalised voiced stops, and nasalised voiceless stops in borrowings and names from foreign languages; for example, ''d'', ''nd'', and ''nt'', which are all written ντ in Greek.

{{IPA|/s/}} and {{IPA|/z/}} are somewhat [[Relative articulation#Advanced and retracted|retracted]] ({{IPA|[s̠, z̠]}}); they are produced in between [[English language|English]] alveolars {{IPA|/s, z/}} and [[postalveolar]]s {{IPA|/ʃ, ʒ/}}.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=12}} {{IPA|/s/}} is variably fronted or further retracted depending on environment, and, in some cases, it may be better described as an advanced postalveolar ({{IPA|[ʃ˖]}}).{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=12}}

The only Greek rhotic {{IPA|/r/}} is prototypically an alveolar tap {{IPAblink|ɾ}}, often retracted ({{IPA|[ɾ̠]}}). It may be an [[alveolar approximant]] {{IPAblink|ɹ}} intervocalically, and is usually a [[alveolar trill|trill]] {{IPAblink|r}} in clusters, with two or three short cycles.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=15}}

Greek has palatals {{IPA|[{{IPA link|c̠|c}}, {{IPA link|ɟ˗|ɟ}}, {{IPA link|ç˗|ç}}, {{IPA link|ʝ˗|ʝ}}]}} that contrast with velars {{IPA|[{{IPA link|k}}, {{IPA link|ɡ}}, {{IPA link|x}}, {{IPA link|ɣ}}]}} before {{IPA|/a, o, u/}}, but in [[complementary distribution]] with velars before front vowels {{IPA|/e, i/}}.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=19}} {{IPAblink|ʎ}} and {{IPAblink|ɲ}} occur as allophones of {{IPA|/l/}} and {{IPA|/n/}}, respectively, in <tt>CJV</tt> (consonant–glide–vowel) clusters, in analyses that posit an [[archiphoneme]]-like [[semivowel|glide]] <tt>/J/</tt> that contrasts with the vowel {{IPA|/i/}}.{{sfn|Baltazani|Topinzi|2013|p=23}} All palatals may be analysed in the same way. The palatal stops and fricatives are somewhat retracted, and {{IPAblink|ʎ}} and {{IPAblink|ɲ}} are somewhat fronted. {{IPAblink|ʎ}} is best described as a postalveolar, and {{IPAblink|ɲ}} as [[alveolo-palatal nasal|alveolo-palatal]].{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=19–20}}

Finally, Greek has two phonetically affricate [[consonant cluster|clusters]], {{IPAblink|t͡s}} and {{IPAblink|d͡z}}.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|pp=20, 23}} {{harvtxt|Arvaniti|2007}} is reluctant to treat these as phonemes on the grounds of inconclusive research into their phonological behaviour.{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=24}}

The table below, adapted from {{harvtxt|Arvaniti|2007|p=25}}, displays a near-full array of consonant phones in Standard Modern Greek.

