===Sandhi===
Some [[assimilation (linguistics)|assimilatory]] processes mentioned above also occur across word boundaries. In particular, this goes for a number of grammatical words ending in {{IPA|/n/}}, most notably the negation particles {{lang|el|δεν}} and {{lang|el|μην}} and the [[Accusative case|accusative]] forms of the personal pronoun and definite article {{lang|el|τον}} and {{lang|el|την}}. If these words are followed by a voiceless stop, {{IPA|/n/}} either assimilates for place of articulation to the stop, or is altogether deleted, and the stop becomes voiced. This results in pronunciations such as {{lang|el|τον πατέρα}} {{IPA|[to(m)baˈtera]}} ('the father' <small>ACC</small>) or {{lang|el|δεν πειράζει}} {{IPA|[ðe(m)biˈrazi]}} ('it doesn't matter'), instead of {{IPA|*[ton paˈtera]}} and {{IPA|*[ðen piˈrazi]}}. The precise extent of assimilation may vary according to dialect, speed and formality of speech.{{sfn|Joseph|Philippaki-Warburton|1987|p=246}}

==Vowels==
[[Image:Standard Modern Greek vowel chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|The vowels of Standard Modern Greek on a [[vowel chart]]. Adapted from {{harvtxt|Arvaniti|2007|p=28}}.]]

Greek has a simple system of five vowels {{IPA|/i, u, e, o, a/}}:{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=25}}{{sfn|Lodge|2009|p=89}}{{sfn|Trudgill|2009|p=81}}
* The closed vowels {{IPA|/i, u/}} have qualities approaching their respective [[cardinal vowels]].{{sfn|Lodge|2009|p=89}}{{sfn|Trudgill|2009|p=81}}{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|pp=25, 28}}
* The mid vowels {{IPA|/e, o/}} are [[Mid vowel|true-mid]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e̞}}, {{IPA link|o̞}}]}}.{{sfn|Lodge|2009|p=89}}{{sfn|Trudgill|2009|p=81}}{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|p=28}}
* The open vowel {{IPA|/a/}} has been described variously as near-open central {{IPAblink|ɐ}}{{sfn|Lodge|2009|p=89}}{{sfn|Arvaniti|2007|pp=25, 28}} and open central {{IPAblink|ä}}.{{sfn|Trudgill|2009|p=81}}

There is no phonemic length distinction, but vowels in stressed syllables are pronounced somewhat longer {{IPA|[iˑ, uˑ, eˑ, oˑ, aˑ]}} than in unstressed syllables. Furthermore, vowels in stressed syllables are more peripheral, but the difference is not large. In casual speech, unstressed {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} in the vicinity of voiceless consonants may become devoiced or even elided.{{sfn|Arvaniti|1999|pp=3, 5}}

