{{Comparison newspaper size.svg}}
'''Newspaper formats''' vary substantially, with different formats more common in different countries. The size of a newspaper format refers to the [[paper size|size of the paper page]]; the printed area within that can vary substantially depending on the newspaper.

In some countries, particular formats have associations with particular types of newspaper; for example, in the [[United Kingdom]], there is a distinction between "tabloid" and "broadsheet" as references to newspaper content quality, which originates with the more popular newspapers using the tabloid format; hence "[[tabloid journalism]]".

==Trends==
{{See also|Broadsheet#Switch to smaller sizes}}
Manfred Werfel Research Director and Vice President of [[IFRA (publishing)|IFRA]] predicts a trend towards the Berliner format.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}

In a recent trend,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naa.org/technology/pressweb/index.html |title=Press web |publisher=Naa.org |date= |accessdate=2010-12-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704154509/http://www.naa.org/technology/pressweb/index.html |archivedate=July 4, 2008 }}</ref> many newspapers have been undergoing what is known as "web cut down", in which the publication is redesigned to print using a narrower (and less expensive) roll of paper.  In extreme examples, some broadsheet papers are nearly as narrow as traditional tabloids.
An average roll of {{convert|26.4|lb|kg|abbr=on}}, {{convert|45|in|cm|abbr=on}} diameter newsprint rolled out is {{convert|9.7|mi|km|abbr=on}} long.

==Sizes and Aspect Ratios==
* [[Diver's Dispatch]] {{convert|914.4|x|609.6|mm|in|abbr=on}} (1.5 aspect ratio)
* [[Broadsheet]] {{convert|749|x|597|mm|in|abbr=on}} (1.255 aspect ratio)
* Nordisch {{convert|570|x|400|mm|in|abbr=on}} (1.425 aspect ratio)
* [[Rhenish (format)|Rhenish]] around {{convert|350|x|520|mm|in|abbr=on}} (1.486 aspect ratio)
* Swiss ([[Neue Zürcher Zeitung]]) {{convert|475|x|320|mm|in|abbr=on}} (1.484 aspect ratio)
* [[Berliner (format)|Berliner]] {{convert|470|x|315|mm|in|abbr=on}} (1.492 aspect ratio)
**The Guardian's ''printed area'' was {{convert|443|x|287|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news|author=Richard Hollis|title=How we got the measure of a Berliner|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/newsroom/story/0,,1566507,00.html}}</ref>
* [[Tabloid_(newspaper_format)|Tabloid]] {{convert|430|x|280|mm|in|abbr=on}} (1.536 aspect ratio)

